# BENCH.log

Throughput log per docs/VERIFICATION.md. Our numbers are tokens/sec for
prefill (512-token prompt) and decode (256 generated), median of 5 runs,
machine plugged in. Measure with tools/bench; force a kernel with
DBINFER_QUANT_KERNEL={scalar,sdot,i8mm}.

Machine: Apple M3 Max, 12 P-cores, 48 GB unified memory.
FEAT_DotProd=1, FEAT_I8MM=1.

## Phase 4 (NEON int8 matvec) — commit c18ff63

Single-threaded. Weights read from the mmap; activations quantized to Q8_0 per
matvec. before = scalar int8-dot reference; after = i8mm (the resolved default
on this host). sdot is the intermediate SIMD step.

qwen2.5-0.5b-q8_0.gguf                prefill tok/s   decode tok/s
  scalar (before)                        13.13          12.60
  sdot                                   13.11          12.59
  i8mm   (after, default)                16.33          15.54

qwen2.5-0.5b-q4_0.gguf                prefill tok/s   decode tok/s
  scalar (before)                        12.81          12.33
  sdot                                   13.33          12.81
  i8mm   (after, default)                17.16          16.29

i8mm vs sdot at m=1: i8mm wins (+23% q8 decode, +27% q4 decode). sdot ties the
scalar reference because clang already vectorizes the int8 loop. m=1 decode is
compute-bound at this model size, so i8mm's 2-row smmla tile helps. i8mm is the
resolved default; sdot and scalar remain for hosts without FEAT_I8MM and as the
1e-6 property-test reference.

Kernel microbench, hot weights, one [out=4864 in=896] matvec, m=1, calls/s:
  q8 scalar 1568   sdot 1563   i8mm 2063
  q4 scalar 1479   sdot 1561   i8mm 2065

## External baseline — llama-bench (build 0bb291933)

tools/llama.cpp/build/bin/llama-bench -m <gguf> -ngl 0 -t 12

  qwen2.5-0.5b-q8_0   pp512 1413.22 t/s   tg128 173.52 t/s
  qwen2.5-0.5b-q4_0   pp512 1400.03 t/s   tg128 227.77 t/s

llama-bench runs 12 threads with an Accelerate BLAS prefill path. This engine
is single-threaded here (threading is Phase 5, an Accelerate prefill path is
Phase 6), so the gap is expected and closes in those phases.

Sanity ceiling: decode tok/s cannot exceed memory_bandwidth / bytes_per_token.
q8_0 is ~500 MB/token, so an M3 Max at ~400 GB/s caps near 800 tok/s. Our
15.5 tok/s sits far below the ceiling, confirming decode here is compute-bound,
not bandwidth-bound.

## Phase 5 — threading (stdlib pool)

Commit: e061c82

stdlib thread pool (std::jthread + condition_variable), no OpenMP. matvec
parallelized over output rows (row tile 2 keeps i8mm smmla pairs intact),
attention parallelized over heads. bitwise identical to single-thread on the
fp32 path (tests/matvec_determinism_test, F16+Q8_0+Q4_0). M3 Max, 12 P-cores.

tools/bench <gguf> 160 96, median of 5. tok/s is per-token so counts differ
from the 512/256 sections above without affecting the rate.

