The single-thread q4_0 16-chunk run is elided for runtime; the 4-chunk pair
and the bitwise determinism test cover the equality claim.

### ThreadSanitizer

build/tsan preset (-fsanitize=thread, cannot combine with ASan). thread_pool_test
and model_test ran with no data-race reports. model_test drives the auto-threaded
decode_layer and matvec_quant path against the goldens (embedding, attention,
layer output, logits). matvec_determinism_test is elided under TSan for runtime;
model_test covers the same threaded kernels in seconds.

## Phase 6 (k-quant perplexity)

WikiText-2 test, n_ctx 512, non-overlapping windows, oracle pinned to fp32 kv.
q4_k_m is the mixed llama.cpp quant (132 q5_0, 13 q8_0, 12 q4_k, 12 q6_k here).
engine vs llama-perplexity on the same gguf:

  q4_k_m  16 chunks   engine 18.1301   oracle 18.0497   +0.45%
  q4_k_m   4 chunks   engine 13.5675   oracle 13.4804   +0.65%
  q6_k    16 chunks   engine 17.7689   oracle 17.6720   +0.55%
  q6_k     4 chunks   engine 13.3314   oracle 13.2303   +0.76%

all within the 1% weight-quant budget (docs/VERIFICATION.md layer 4).

## Phase 6 (Accelerate prefill)

matmul_accel dequantizes the weight once then issues one cblas_sgemm
(-framework Accelerate, DBINFER_HAVE_ACCELERATE). measured against the scalar
reference matmul (the naive triple loop, not the NEON matvec) on a 512-row
batch, tests/accel_matmul_test. M3 Max, single call, average of 20.

  matmul [m=512 out=512 in=896]   scalar 156.463 ms   accel 0.316 ms   494x

max abs error accel vs scalar 1.5e-5, within the 1e-3 GEMM tolerance. the
wrapper is not wired into forward(): decode still runs one token at a time, so
the default decode path and its perplexity are byte-for-byte unchanged. the
figure sizes the headroom a batched prefill would unlock against the scalar
reference, and is the reason llama-bench's pp512 outruns this engine.

## Phase 7 (KV cache streaming) — 2026-07-19

Ring-buffer KV cache with attention sinks (StreamingLLM), behind --kv-window.
Streaming perplexity feeds one continuous context with monotonically rising
position, per-token NLL bucketed every 512 positions. WikiText-2 test,
qwen2.5-0.5b F16, window 256, first 8 buckets (4096 tokens).

  ./build/release/engine -m qwen2.5-0.5b.gguf --perplexity wiki.test.raw \
    --ppl-stream --kv-window 256 --kv-sink {0,4} --ppl-chunks 8

  pos          naive (sink 0)   sinks (sink 4)
  0-511            95.6956          16.2858
  512-1023         93.9265          19.4518
  1024-1535       105.8915          17.3745
  1536-2047        90.3526          18.2041
  2048-2559        78.8882          14.3412
  2560-3071       117.9712          19.4920
  3072-3583       115.2568          18.2693
  3584-4095       114.7031          21.7222
  stream PPL      100.704792        18.018553

past the 256-token window the naive ring evicts the initial tokens and stays
stuck near 90-118. four pinned sinks hold it flat at 14-22, tracking the dense
full-context range. sinks are the whole difference; without them the ring is
unusable. --ppl-stream requires --kv-window > 0 (the dense cache would run pos
past context_length). default decode, parity, and dense perplexity unchanged.

### int8 KV (--kv-int8), dense, WikiText-2 16 chunks

  ./build/release/engine -m qwen2.5-0.5b.gguf --perplexity wiki.test.raw \
    --ppl-chunks 16 [--kv-int8] [--kv-sink N]

  fp32 KV                                       17.699375
  int8 KV, per-head absmax scale                18.854920   +6.53%
  int8 KV, per-block(32) scale                  18.275141   +3.25%
  int8 KV, per-channel K, no fp32 sink          17.715029   +0.089%
  int8 KV, per-channel K + 4 fp32 sinks         17.710983   +0.066%

per-token quant (per-head or per-block-32) loses 3-6% because one spiking K
channel inflates the scale for its whole slice, crushing the rest. K outliers
are channel-consistent (KIVI), so a scale per head_dim channel, shared across a
32-token group and requantized from a small fp32 residual as the group fills,
cuts the loss to 0.089% on its own. pinning the first 4 tokens (BOS and the
attention sinks, the outlier tokens) in fp32 trims it to 0.066%. values stay
per-block(32) per-token. both configs meet the 0.5% budget; the shipped default
is per-channel K + 4 fp32 sinks (--kv-sink 4). --kv-int8 stays opt-in and the
fp32 dense cache is the default, byte-for-byte unchanged (PPL 17.699375 here
matches the pre-change run and matvec_determinism_test stays bitwise).

## Phase 8 (GBNF grammar-constrained decoding)

Grammar masking tests every vocabulary token against the automaton per decode
step and sets rejected tokens to -inf before the sampler pipeline. Measured on
qwen2.5-0.5b Q8_0, prompt "Write JSON:\n", temp 1.0, seed 5, engine mask
single-threaded. tok/s is the two-length delta 200/(wall(216)-wall(16)) so the
fixed model-load and prefill cancel.

  ./build/release/engine -m qwen2.5-0.5b-q8_0.gguf -p "Write JSON:\n" \
    --temp 1.0 -s 5 -n {16,216} [--grammar grammars/json.gbnf]

  grammar off   90.09 tok/s
  grammar on    12.94 tok/s   +66.2 ms/token   6.96x

overhead is the per-step scan of the 151936-token vocabulary. most tokens are
rejected at their first codepoint. the batch harness (tools/grammar_json_gen)
splits that scan across the 12 P-cores, holding ~1.5 s/generation including the
model forward.

### JSON gate: 1000 completions

  ./build/release/tools/grammar_json_gen -m qwen2.5-0.5b-q8_0.gguf \
    -g grammars/json.gbnf -c 1000 -n 64 --temp 1.0 -p "Return one JSON object:\n"
  tools/.venv/bin/python -c "json.loads each line"

  1000/1000 parse as valid JSON  (671 completed naturally, 329 closed along the
  shortest grammar-valid suffix when the 64-token sampling budget ran out).

## Phase 9 (speculative decoding)

A quantized draft (qwen2.5-0.5b Q4_0) proposes k tokens greedily; the F16
target (qwen2.5-0.5b) verifies them in one forward_chunk over k+1 positions,
accepting the longest prefix where the draft token equals the target's greedy
argmax and taking the target's argmax on the first mismatch. Greedy, so the
output is token-identical to target-only decode by construction.

Token-identical gate (--print-ids, greedy, diff vs spec off), n 64:

  ./build/release/engine -m qwen2.5-0.5b.gguf -p "<prompt>" -n 64 --print-ids \
    [--draft-model qwen2.5-0.5b-q4_0.gguf --draft-k {4,8}]

  prompt "The quick brown fox"              k=4 IDENTICAL  rate 0.7656
  prompt "The quick brown fox"              k=8 IDENTICAL  rate 0.6591
  prompt "Once upon a time in a distant land" k=4 IDENTICAL  rate 0.6000
  prompt "Once upon a time in a distant land" k=8 IDENTICAL  rate 0.3487

Wall clock, prompt "Once upon a time in a distant land", 12 P-cores, decode
delta 128/(wall(144)-wall(16)) so model load and prefill cancel, median of 3:

  spec off        8.54 tok/s
  spec on k=4     9.62 tok/s   1.13x

  (prior fused-free number was spec on k=4 4.80 tok/s, 0.55x.)

matmul_quant now runs a fused batched f16 kernel on the verify path: each
weight element is dequantized once and accumulated into all k+1 token rows, so
the target weights are read from the mmap once per round instead of k+1 times.
The reduction over `in` stays sequential and uses explicit std::fma, matched by
the same std::fma in the per-row matvec_f16, so every verify logit is
bit-identical to per-token decode (chunked_prefill_test, matvec_determinism_test)
and the greedy stream stays token-identical to spec-off (--print-ids diff,
k=4 and k=8, both prompts IDENTICAL). Speedup is now above 1x because the
verify projections are no longer weight-bandwidth-bound on the k+1 rows.
